04891nam a22006255i 9780822387299DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223872997 a10.1515/97808223872992doi  a(DE-B1597)554218  a(OCoLC)1226679647  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE169.12b.M425 2005 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aMedovoi, Leerom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRebels :bYouth and the Cold War Origins of Identity /cLeerom Medovoi; Donald E. Pease. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (398 p.) :b37 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Identitarian Thought and the Cold War World -- t2. Cold War Literature and the National Allegory: The Identity Canon of Holden Caulfield -- t3. Transcommodification: Rock 'n' Roll and the Suburban Counterimaginary -- t4. Identity Hits the Screen: Teenpics and the Boying of Rebellion -- t5. Oedipus in Suburbia: Bad Boys and the Fordist Family Drama -- t6. Beat Fraternity and the Generation of Identity -- t7. Where the Girls Were: Figuring the Female Rebel -- tConclusion: The Rise and Fall of Identity -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHolden Caulfield, the beat writers, Elvis Presley, Chuck Berry, and James Dean-these and other avatars of youthful rebellion were much more than entertainment. As Leerom Medovoi shows, they were often embraced and hotly debated at the dawn of the Cold War era because they stood for dissent and defiance at a time when the ideological production of the United States as leader of the "free world" required emancipatory figures who could represent America's geopolitical claims. Medovoi argues that the "bad boy" became a guarantor of the country's anti-authoritarian, democratic self-image: a kindred spirit to the freedom-seeking nations of the rapidly decolonizing third world and a counterpoint to the repressive conformity attributed to both the Soviet Union abroad and America's burgeoning suburbs at home.Alongside the young rebel, the contemporary concept of identity emerged in the 1950s. It was in that decade that "identity" was first used to define collective selves in the politicized manner that is recognizable today: in terms such as "national identity" and "racial identity." Medovoi traces the rapid absorption of identity themes across many facets of postwar American culture, including beat literature, the young adult novel, the Hollywood teen film, early rock 'n' roll, black drama, and "bad girl" narratives. He demonstrates that youth culture especially began to exhibit telltale motifs of teen, racial, sexual, gender, and generational revolt that would burst into political prominence during the ensuing decades, bequeathing to the progressive wing of contemporary American political culture a potent but ambiguous legacy of identity politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAlienation (Social psychology) in literature. 0aAlienation (Social psychology) in motion pictures. 0aAlienation (Social psychology)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aGroup identityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aYouth in literature. 0aYouth in motion pictures. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aPease, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387299zCo-access DOI >> cli